<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,914,525,587]" box="[151,914,525,551]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,914,525,551]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,914,525,551]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<taxonomicName authority="Laurent, 1949" authorityName="Laurent" authorityYear="1949" box="[151,607,525,551]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Trilepida" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,405,525,551]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Trilepida brasiliensis</emphasis>
(Laurent, 
<number box="[538,598,525,551]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1949.0">1949</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
“Cobra-de-chumbinho”
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,914,525,587]" box="[151,370,562,587]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">(Figs. 8.4 and 21.2)</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,637,848]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Recorded in the states of Ceará, Paraíba, and Bahia. Widely distributed in central Brazilian highlands, ranging from 
<quantity box="[151,303,674,699]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.085" metricValueMax="7.17" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="m" value="608.5" valueMax="717.0" valueMin="500.0">500 to 717 m</quantity>
elevation, and also recorded marginally in Caatinga lowlands (
<quantity box="[1021,1095,674,699]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.52" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="m" value="452.0">452 m</quantity>
elevation) in Barreiras, Bahia State. It is considered widely distributed in Cerrado (
<bibRefCitation author="Curcio" box="[768,985,711,736]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refString="Curcio, F., Zaher, H. &amp; Rodrigues, M. T. (2002) Rediscovery of the blind-snake Leptotyphlops brasiliensis Laurent, 1949 (Serpentes, Leptotyphlopidae) in the wild. Phyllomedusa, 1, 101 - 104. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11606 / issn. 2316 - 9079. v 1 i 2 p 101 - 104" type="journal article" year="2002">
Curcio 
<emphasis box="[856,916,711,736]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[926,985,712,736]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Nogueira" box="[1000,1244,711,736]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refString="Nogueira, C., Colli, G. R., Costa, G. &amp; Machado, R. B. (2010) Diversidade de repteis Squamata e evolucao do conhecimento faunistico no Cerrado. In: Diniz, I. R., Marinho-Filho, J., Machado, R. B. &amp; Cavalcanti, R. B. (Eds.), Cerrado: conhecimento cientifico quantitativo como subsidio para acoes de conservacao. Editora UNB, Brasilia, pp. 333 - 375." type="book chapter" year="2010">
Nogueira 
<emphasis box="[1115,1167,711,736]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[1184,1244,712,736]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2010.0">2010</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pinto" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refString="Pinto, R. R. &amp; Curcio, F. F. (2011) On the generic identify of Siagonodon brasiliensis, with the description of a new Leptotyphlopid from Central Brazil (Serpentes: Leptotyphlopidae). Copeia, 1, 53 - 63. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1643 / CH- 09 - 119" type="journal article" year="2011">
Pinto &amp; Curcio 
<number box="[151,210,750,774]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), associated to savannas over sandy soils (
<bibRefCitation author="Vitt" box="[686,862,749,774]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refString="Vitt, L. J., Caldwell, J. P., Colli, G. R., Garda, A., Mesquita, D. O., Franca, F. G. &amp; Balbino, S. F. (2002) Um guia fotografico dos repteis e anfibios da regiao do Jalapao no Cerrado brasileiro. Special publications in Herpetology, Sam Noble Oklahoma Museum of Natural History, 1, 1 - 17." type="journal article" year="2002">
Vitt 
<emphasis box="[737,787,749,774]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[801,862,750,774]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). It inhabits portions of cerrado in highlands inside Caatinga (Borges-Nojosa 
<emphasis box="[443,500,786,811]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[508,569,787,811]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2009.0">2009</number>
). The species has fossorial habits, is nocturnal and diurnal, and feeds mostly on arthropods (
<bibRefCitation author="Curcio" box="[320,527,823,848]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refString="Curcio, F., Zaher, H. &amp; Rodrigues, M. T. (2002) Rediscovery of the blind-snake Leptotyphlops brasiliensis Laurent, 1949 (Serpentes, Leptotyphlopidae) in the wild. Phyllomedusa, 1, 101 - 104. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11606 / issn. 2316 - 9079. v 1 i 2 p 101 - 104" type="journal article" year="2002">
Curcio 
<emphasis box="[405,461,823,848]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[468,527,824,848]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pinto" box="[539,777,823,848]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refString="Pinto, R. R. &amp; Curcio, F. F. (2011) On the generic identify of Siagonodon brasiliensis, with the description of a new Leptotyphlopid from Central Brazil (Serpentes: Leptotyphlopidae). Copeia, 1, 53 - 63. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1643 / CH- 09 - 119" type="journal article" year="2011">
Pinto &amp; Curcio 
<number box="[717,777,824,848]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
